TY  - JOUR
T1  - Markets, power and productivity in rural Asia: A review article
AU  - Bell, Clive
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 36
IS  - 2
SP  - 373
EP  - 393
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/10/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(91)90042-T
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030438789190042T
AB  - This article deals with three themes. First, the evidence that rural markets are responsive to scarcity is open to two interpretations: (i) that markets closely approach the competitive ideal; and (ii) that such responses are also consistent with various market imperfections. Second, there is the nature of power and its influence on economic transactions. Lacking a satisfactory definition of the concept, many contributions dealing with power yield few insights. Third, there is the relationship between agrarian structure and economic progress. A signal accomplishment of some contributions has been to show that South Asia's diverse experience casts considerable doubt on the proposition that this relationship is a simple one.
ER  - 

